MCP Server
An MCP server is a program that exposes data, tools, or capabilities to an AI assistant using the Model Context Protocol (MCP) — an open standard that enables developers to build secure, two-way connections between their data sources and AI-powered tools. Anthropic open-sourced MCP as a new standard for connecting AI assistants to the systems where data lives, including content repositories, business tools, and development environments, in November 2024.
Why it exists: Without a shared standard, every AI app would need a custom integration for every tool — an "N×M integration problem" where N tools and M AI clients would otherwise require N×M separate integrations. MCP reduces that to N+M by having each client and server implement the protocol just once. It's often compared to a USB-C port for AI: one standard connector instead of a different cable for every device.
How it fits together:
* MCP host — the AI application itself, like an AI-powered IDE or conversational AI, where the LLM lives.
* MCP client — sits inside the host, translates the LLM's requests into MCP messages, and finds/uses available MCP servers.
* MCP server — the external service that actually provides context, data, or capabilities — connecting to things like databases and web services and translating their responses into a format the LLM can use.
What a server can expose: according to Anthropic's docs, MCP servers expose data through Resources (read-only data retrieval), Tools (actions that can perform a side effect, like a calculation or an API call), and Prompts (reusable templates for common workflows).
A concrete example: if you ask an assistant to "find the latest sales report and email it to my manager," the LLM realizes it can't query a database or send email on its own, so it uses the MCP client to discover a database_query tool and an email_sender tool registered on MCP servers, calls them in sequence, and the MCP server confirms once the action is done.
Adoption: MCP spread quickly beyond Anthropic — OpenAI adopted it in March 2025 and Google DeepMind followed, and in December 2025 Anthropic donated MCP to the Agentic AI Foundation, a Linux Foundation project co-founded by Anthropic, Block, and OpenAI.
One caution worth knowing: because MCP servers can execute code and touch real data, a poorly implemented server can create a "confused deputy" problem where it acts beyond what the user actually permitted, and a malicious server could look safe at install time but change tool behavior later — which is why the servers you connect Claude to should come from sources you trust.
You've actually already been using this concept — the "connectors" I can suggest (like task managers, calendars, or restaurant booking apps) are MCP servers under the hood.
